        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <div type="transcription">
                    
<p>I think that a brown study is merely another version of the same metaphor which speaks of a <hi rend="underline">sombre</hi> countenance, ein <hi rend="underline">düsteres</hi> gesicht<ref target="#foot.f2"/> <hi rend="underline">Heiter</hi> and <hi rend="underline">düster</hi> express chearful and moody as being open to light and external influences or closed and shut up within itself.<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The date range is established from the relationship between this letter and the first <ref target="./DCP-LETT-7041.xml">letter from Hensleigh Wedgwood, [1867–72]</ref></note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD used the phrase ‘in a brown study’ for abstraction and meditation in <hi rend="italic">Expression</hi>, p. 228.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">Wedgwood was a philologist: the italicised words (except for ‘sombre’) are German.</note>
        </div>        
            
